# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: aerospike-db
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:aerospike-db/architecture] Aerospike is a massively scalable, millisecond latency, distributed database.
[src:aerospike-db/architecture] The Aerospike clients are implemented as an open source linkable library available in C, Java, Go, C#, Python, Node.js .
[src:aerospike-db/architecture] To see the complete list, go to clients download.
[src:aerospike-db/architecture] Aerospike’s architecture reduces transaction latency, offloads request routing from the cluster, and eliminates the developer’s need to write configuration, data sharding and caching code into their applications.
[src:aerospike-db/architecture] It ensures that applications do not have to be restarted or modified when nodes are brought down or added to the cluster.
[src:aerospike-db/architecture] You do not have to waste time with cluster setup, cluster management, or running proxies.
[src:aerospike-db/architecture] For more information, see Client architecture.
[src:aerospike-db/architecture] The Aerospike “shared nothing” architecture is designed to scale linearly while reliably storing terabytes and petabytes of data.
[src:aerospike-db/architecture] The Distribution layer is designed to eliminate manual operations with the systematic automation of all cluster management functions.
[src:aerospike-db/architecture] Once the first is cluster up, you can install additional clusters in other datacenters and setup cross-datacenter replication to ensure that if a datacenter goes down, the remote cluster takes over the workload with minimal or no interruption to users.
[src:aerospike-db/architecture] For more information, see Clustering and Data distribution.
[src:aerospike-db/architecture] Aerospike is a multi-model (key-value, document, graph) data store with a schemaless data model.
[src:aerospike-db/architecture] Data flows into policy containers, *namespaces*, which are semantically similar to *databases* in an RDBMS.
[src:aerospike-db/architecture] Within a namespace, data is subdivided into *sets* (RDBMS *tables*) and *records* (RDBMS *rows*).
[src:aerospike-db/architecture] Each record has an indexed *key* unique in the set, and one or more named *bins* (RDBMS *columns*) that hold values associated with the record.
[src:aerospike-db/architecture] Indexes, including the primary index and optional secondary indexes, are stored by default in DRAM for ultra-fast access.
[src:aerospike-db/architecture] The primary index can also be configured to be stored in Persistent Memory or on an NVMe flash device.
[src:aerospike-db/architecture] Values can be stored either in DRAM or more cost-effectively on SSDs.
[src:aerospike-db/architecture] You can configure each namespace separately, so small namespaces can take advantage of DRAM and larger ones gain the cost benefits of SSDs.
[src:aerospike-db/architecture] For more information, see Flexible storage.
[src:aerospike-db/architecture] In a conventional, non-distributed RDBMS, after installation you set up your database schema and create databases and table definitions.
[src:aerospike-db/architecture] In distributed databases, data is distributed between all servers in the cluster.
[src:aerospike-db/architecture] That means you cannot simply log onto a server to access all of your data.
[src:aerospike-db/architecture] To provide quality performance and redundancy, plan and configure how many nodes are required.
[src:aerospike-db/architecture] For more information, see Capacity planning guide.
[src:aerospike-db/architecture] If you add a node to the cluster or take down a node for upgrading or servicing, the cluster automatically reconfigures.
[src:aerospike-db/architecture] When a node fails, other nodes in the cluster rebalance the workload with minimal impact.
[src:aerospike-db/architecture] For a list of available monitoring utilities, see Monitoring.
[src:aerospike-db/architecture] With a namespace defined, you can use the Aerospike tools to verify that the database is storing data correctly.
[src:aerospike-db/architecture] In production databases, data is distributed over the cluster.
[src:aerospike-db/architecture] To perform database operations, use the client that instantiates your application.
[src:aerospike-db/architecture] The client is location-aware and knows how to store and retrieve data without affecting performance.
[src:aerospike-db/architecture] On application compilation, the Aerospike API libraries are included along with the client.
[src:aerospike-db/architecture] The client is a separate thread/process that monitors cluster state to determine data location, which ensures that data is retrieved in a single hop and allows your application to ignore the data distribution details.
[src:aerospike-db/blob-readme-md] Welcome to the Aerospike Database Server source code tree!
[src:aerospike-db/blob-readme-md] Aerospike is a distributed, scalable NoSQL database.
[src:aerospike-db/blob-readme-md] The Aerospike Database Server can be built and deployed on various current 64-bit GNU/Linux platform versions, such as Red Hat Enterprise Linux 8/9, Amazon Linux 2023, Debian 11 or later, and Ubuntu 20.04 or later.
[src:aerospike-db/blob-readme-md] The majority of the Aerospike source code is written in the C programming language, conforming to the ANSI C99 standard.
[src:aerospike-db/blob-readme-md] To install dependencies for a development environment run `./bin/install-dependencies.sh` in the aerospike-server repo.
[src:aerospike-db/blob-readme-md] The C++ compiler is required for the Aerospike geospatial indexing feature and its dependency, Google's S2 Geometry Library (both written in C++.) C++ is also used for yaml/json configuration parsing.
[src:aerospike-db/blob-readme-md] As this project uses submodules, the source archive downloadable via GitHub's `Download ZIP` button will not build unless the correct revision of each submodule is first manually installed in the appropriate `modules` subdirectory.
[src:aerospike-db/blob-readme-md] Aerospike collects telemetry information about builds.
[src:aerospike-db/blob-readme-md] To opt out, the environment variable AEROSPIKE_TELEMETRY must be set to FALSE.
[src:aerospike-db/blob-readme-md] You can use the `-j` option with `make` to speed up the build on multiple CPU cores.
[src:aerospike-db/blob-readme-md] Supply a YAML based configuration file that adheres to the schema.
[src:aerospike-db/blob-readme-md] The `asconfig` tool currently outputs an older yaml config format, which is not the same as the experimental YAML format the server validates.
[src:aerospike-db/blob-readme-md] Update the generated YAML to match the server’s schema.
[src:aerospike-db/blob-readme-md] For the authoritative format, reference `/opt/aerospike/schema/aerospike_config_schema.json`.
[src:aerospike-db/blob-readme-md] **Remove `name` fields** that were used inside array entries; the name now becomes the map key.
[src:aerospike-db/blob-readme-md] **(Optional) Use unit-aware values** for size/time settings.
[src:aerospike-db/blob-readme-md] Optionally use `{ value, unit }` objects where supported.
[src:aerospike-db/blob-readme-md] Refer to the schema for the authoritative list of unit-capable fields and allowed units.
[src:aerospike-db/blob-readme-md] YAML configuration as output by asconfig.
[src:aerospike-db/blob-readme-md] The configuration after aligning it with the database schema.
[src:aerospike-db/blob-readme-md] Logging section after aligning it with the database schema.
[src:aerospike-db/blob-readme-md] See `/opt/aerospike/schema/aerospike_config_schema.json` for the full list of logging contexts and the allowed syslog facilities.
[src:aerospike-db/blob-readme-md] The database's experimental yaml configuration format allows certain configs to use values with units.
[src:aerospike-db/blob-readme-md] See `/opt/aerospike/schema/aerospike_config_schema.json` for the definitive list of fields that accept units, the allowed unit values, and the `{ value, unit }` form.
[src:aerospike-db/blob-readme-md] These sample files may be modified for specific use cases (e.g., setting network addresses, defining namespaces, and setting storage engine properties) and tuned for maximum performance on a particular system.
[src:aerospike-db/blob-readme-md] Also, system resource limits may need to be increased to allow, e.g., a greater number of concurrent connections to the database.
[src:aerospike-db/blob-readme-md] There are several options for running the Aerospike database.
[src:aerospike-db/blob-readme-md] Which option to use depends upon whether the primary purpose is production deployment or software development.
[src:aerospike-db/blob-readme-md] Please refer to the full documentation on the Aerospike web site, `https://docs.aerospike.com/`, for more detailed information about configuring and running the Aerospike Database Server, as well as about the Aerospike client API packages for popular programming languages.
[src:aerospike-db/key-value-database] A **key-value database**, or **key-value store**, is a data storage paradigm designed for storing, retrieving, and managing associative arrays, a data structure more commonly known today as a *dictionary*.
[src:aerospike-db/key-value-database] Dictionaries contain a collection of *objects*, or *records*, which in turn have many different *fields* within them.
[src:aerospike-db/key-value-database] These records are stored and retrieved using a *key* that uniquely identifies the record, and is used to find the data within the database.
[src:aerospike-db/key-value-database] Key-value databases differ from the better known relational databases (RDB).
[src:aerospike-db/key-value-database] RDBs pre-define the data structure in the database as a series of tables containing fields with well-defined data types.
[src:aerospike-db/key-value-database] Exposing the data types to the database program allows it to apply various optimizations.
[src:aerospike-db/key-value-database] In contrast, key-value systems treat the value as opaque to the database itself, and typically support only simple operations such as storing, retrieving, updating, and deleting a value by its key.
[src:aerospike-db/key-value-database] This offers considerable flexibility and makes such systems well suited to low-latency, high-throughput workloads dominated by direct key lookups, but less suitable for applications that require complex queries or explicit relationships among records.
[src:aerospike-db/key-value-database] A lack of standardization, limited transaction support, and relatively simple query interfaces long restricted many key-value systems to specialized uses, but the rapid move to cloud computing after 2010 helped drive renewed interest in them as part of the broader NoSQL movement.
[src:aerospike-db/key-value-database] Some graph databases, such as ArangoDB, are also key–value databases internally, adding the concept of relationships (*pointers*) between records as a first-class data type.
[src:aerospike-db/key-value-database] Key–value systems span a wide consistency spectrum, from eventually consistent designs to strongly consistent or serializable ones, and some allow the consistency level to be configured as part of the trade-off against latency and availability.
[src:aerospike-db/key-value-database] Renewed interest in key–value and other NoSQL systems was driven in part by the demands of big data, distributed, and cloud applications.
[src:aerospike-db/key-value-database] Their scalability and availability made them attractive for cloud data management, although limited transaction support, low-level query interfaces, and the lack of standardization remained obstacles to wider adoption.
[src:aerospike-db/key-value-database] Some maintain data in memory (RAM), while others employ solid-state drives or rotating disks.
[src:aerospike-db/key-value-database] Some key–value systems add additional structure to their keys.
[src:aerospike-db/key-value-database] For example, Oracle NoSQL Database organizes records using composite keys with "major" and "minor" components, an arrangement that Oracle compares to a directory-path structure in a file system.
[src:aerospike-db/key-value-database] More generally, however, key–value stores are defined by their use of unique keys associated with opaque values and by their emphasis on simple key-based operations.
[src:aerospike-db/key-value-database] Unix included *dbm* (database manager), a minimal database library written by Ken Thompson for managing associative arrays with a single key and hash-based access.
[src:aerospike-db/key-value-database] Later implementations and related libraries included sdbm, GNU dbm (gdbm), and Berkeley DB.
[src:aerospike-db/key-value-database] A more recent example is RocksDB, a persistent key–value storage engine developed at Facebook and designed for large-scale applications.
[src:aerospike-db/key-value-database] Other examples include in-memory systems such as Memcached and Redis, and persistent systems such as Berkeley DB, Riak, and Voldemort.
[src:aerospike-db/nosql] NoSQL databases are popular in big data and real-time web applications due to their simple design, ability to scale across clusters of machines (called horizontal scaling), and precise control over data availability.
[src:aerospike-db/nosql] These structures can speed up certain tasks and are often considered more adaptable than fixed database tables.
[src:aerospike-db/nosql] However, many NoSQL systems prioritize speed and availability over strict consistency (per the CAP theorem), using eventual consistency—where updates reach all nodes eventually, typically within milliseconds, but may cause brief delays in accessing the latest data, known as stale reads.
[src:aerospike-db/nosql] While most lack full ACID transaction support, some, like MongoDB, include it as a key feature.
[src:aerospike-db/nosql] Barriers to wider NoSQL adoption include their use of low-level query languages instead of SQL, inability to perform ad hoc joins across tables, lack of standardized interfaces, and significant investments already made in relational databases.
[src:aerospike-db/nosql] Some NoSQL systems risk losing data through lost writes or other forms, though features like write-ahead logging—a method to record changes before they’re applied—can help prevent this.
[src:aerospike-db/nosql] Limitations within the interface environment are overcome using semantic virtualization protocols, such that NoSQL services are accessible to most operating systems.
[src:aerospike-db/nosql] The term *NoSQL* was used by Carlo Strozzi in 1998 to name his lightweight Strozzi NoSQL open-source relational database that did not expose the standard Structured Query Language (SQL) interface, but was still relational.
[src:aerospike-db/nosql] His NoSQL RDBMS is distinct from the around-2009 general concept of NoSQL databases.
[src:aerospike-db/nosql] Strozzi suggests that, because the current NoSQL movement "departs from the relational model altogether, it should therefore have been called more appropriately 'NoREL'", referring to "not relational".
[src:aerospike-db/nosql] Johan Oskarsson, then a developer at Last.fm, reintroduced the term *NoSQL* in early 2009 when he organized an event to discuss "open-source distributed, non-relational databases".
[src:aerospike-db/nosql] The name attempted to label the emergence of an increasing number of non-relational, distributed data stores, including open source clones of Google's Bigtable/MapReduce and Amazon's DynamoDB.
[src:aerospike-db/nosql] There are various ways to classify NoSQL databases, with different categories and subcategories, some of which overlap.
[src:aerospike-db/nosql] Key–value (KV) stores use the associative array (also called a map or dictionary) as their fundamental data model.
[src:aerospike-db/nosql] In this model, data is represented as a collection of key–value pairs, such that each possible key appears at most once in the collection.
[src:aerospike-db/nosql] The key–value model is one of the simplest non-trivial data models, and richer data models are often implemented as an extension of it.
[src:aerospike-db/nosql] The key–value model can be extended to a discretely ordered model that maintains keys in lexicographic order.
[src:aerospike-db/nosql] This extension is computationally powerful, in that it can efficiently retrieve selective key *ranges*.
[src:aerospike-db/nosql] Key–value stores can use consistency models ranging from eventual consistency to serializability.
[src:aerospike-db/nosql] Some databases support ordering of keys.
[src:aerospike-db/nosql] There are various hardware implementations, and some users store data in memory (RAM), while others on solid-state drives (SSD) or rotating disks (aka hard disk drive (HDD)).
[src:aerospike-db/nosql] The central concept of a document store is that of a "document".
[src:aerospike-db/nosql] While the details of this definition differ among document-oriented databases, they all assume that documents encapsulate and encode data (or information) in some standard formats or encodings.
[src:aerospike-db/nosql] Encodings in use include XML, YAML, and JSON and binary forms like BSON.
[src:aerospike-db/nosql] Documents are addressed in the database via a unique *key* that represents that document.
[src:aerospike-db/nosql] Another defining characteristic of a document-oriented database is an API or query language to retrieve documents based on their contents.
[src:aerospike-db/nosql] Compared to relational databases, collections could be considered analogous to tables and documents analogous to records.
[src:aerospike-db/nosql] But they are different – every record in a table has the same sequence of fields, while documents in a collection may have fields that are completely different.
[src:aerospike-db/nosql] Graph databases are designed for data whose relations are well represented as a graph consisting of elements connected by a finite number of relations.
[src:aerospike-db/nosql] Examples of data include social relations, public transport links, road maps, network topologies, etc.
[src:aerospike-db/nosql] The performance of NoSQL databases is usually evaluated using the metric of throughput, which is measured as operations per second.
[src:aerospike-db/nosql] Performance evaluation must pay attention to the right benchmarks such as production configurations, parameters of the databases, anticipated data volume, and concurrent user workloads.
[src:aerospike-db/nosql] Performance and scalability comparisons are most commonly done using the YCSB benchmark.
[src:aerospike-db/nosql] Since most NoSQL databases lack ability for joins in queries, the database schema generally needs to be designed differently.
[src:aerospike-db/nosql] There are three main techniques for handling relational data in a NoSQL database.
[src:aerospike-db/nosql] Instead of retrieving all the data with one query, it is common to do several queries to get the desired data.
[src:aerospike-db/nosql] NoSQL queries are often faster than traditional SQL queries, so the cost of additional queries may be acceptable.
[src:aerospike-db/nosql] If an excessive number of queries would be necessary, one of the other two approaches is more appropriate.
[src:aerospike-db/nosql] Instead of only storing foreign keys, it is common to store actual foreign values along with the model's data.
[src:aerospike-db/nosql] For example, each blog comment might include the username in addition to a user id, thus providing easy access to the username without requiring another lookup.
[src:aerospike-db/nosql] When a username changes, however, this will now need to be changed in many places in the database.
[src:aerospike-db/nosql] Thus this approach works better when reads are much more common than writes.
[src:aerospike-db/nosql] With document databases like MongoDB it is common to put more data in a smaller number of collections.
[src:aerospike-db/nosql] For example, in a blogging application, one might choose to store comments within the blog post document, so that with a single retrieval one gets all the comments.
[src:aerospike-db/nosql] Thus in this approach a single document contains all the data needed for a specific task.
[src:aerospike-db/nosql] A database is marked as supporting ACID properties (atomicity, consistency, isolation, durability) or join operations if the documentation for the database makes that claim.
[src:aerospike-db/nosql] However, this doesn't necessarily mean that the capability is fully supported in a manner similar to most SQL databases.
[src:aerospike-db/nosql] MongoDB did not support joining from a sharded collection until version 5.1.
[src:aerospike-db/nosql] OrientDB can resolve 1:1 joins using links by storing direct links to foreign records.
[src:aerospike-db/nosql] Different NoSQL databases, such as DynamoDB, MongoDB, Cassandra, Couchbase, HBase, and Redis, exhibit varying behaviors when querying non-indexed fields.
[src:aerospike-db/nosql] Many perform full-table or collection scans for such queries, applying filtering operations after retrieving data.
[src:aerospike-db/nosql] However, modern NoSQL databases often incorporate advanced features to optimize query performance.
[src:aerospike-db/nosql] For example, MongoDB supports compound indexes and query-optimization strategies, Cassandra offers secondary indexes and materialized views, and Redis employs custom indexing mechanisms tailored to specific use cases.
[src:aerospike-db/nosql] Systems like Elasticsearch use inverted indexes for efficient text-based searches, but they can still require full scans for non-indexed fields.
[src:aerospike-db/nosql] This behavior reflects the design focus of many NoSQL systems on scalability and efficient key-based operations rather than optimized querying for arbitrary fields.
[src:aerospike-db/nosql] Consequently, while these databases excel at basic CRUD operations and key-based lookups, their suitability for complex queries involving joins or non-indexed filtering varies depending on the database type—document, key–value, wide-column, or graph—and the specific implementation.
[src:aerospike-db/page] The high-performance, distributed, NoSQL database designed for real-time applications requiring low latency and high availability.
